inv:Dataset.inv:Title: Payments over £500
inv:Dataset.inv:Description:
Payments made to suppliers where the invoice total amounts to over £500.  Note that a single invoice may be represented by multiple lines in the payment data and as such some lines may contain amounts under £500.

Some data may appear as Redacted Personal Data. This personal data is protected by the Data Protection Act 1998 to prevent any individual being identified.

This data will be published in the middle of each following month. So data for October is published mid November and so on. This is simply to allow us to run the appropriate data gathering exercise.

inv:Dataset.inv:Title: Budget
inv:Dataset.inv:Description:
The budget which the Council is working to for the financial year and has been agreed by the full Council meeting. This excludes unallocated contigencies.

The Council’s Revenue Budget for 2011/12 is £200.6 million which, when compared to the equivalent figure for 2010/11, is a decrease in spending of £9.5 million (4.5%).  Spending reductions have primarily been driven by the significant funding cuts imposed across the public sector by Central Government.  In meeting this challenge and in order to deliver a freeze in Council Tax the authority has given its highest priority to identifying and delivering savings through back office support and/or efficiency measures wherever this has been possible.

Admissions - Community Primary School - Reception Allocations Overview of Oversubscribed Schools 2008

The following information attached gives you a little more detail about the allocations procedure. It gives you the cut of points/distances by which the last child was offered a place at oversubscribed community primary schools, in accordance with the Authority’s agreed admissions criteria. You should read this information carefully, but please bear in mind that the allocations process continues as vacancies arise, so these details are only accurate at the time this sheet was printed on 29 April 2008.

 

It is important to note that offers are made according to how you ranked your preferred schools and whether your child met the criteria for those schools.

 

For Redbridge schools, which are their own admitting authorities- these are the Catholic primary schools, Jewish schools and Church schools, for details of how places were allocated you should contact the school directly.

inv:Dataset.inv:Description:
Admissions - Community Secondary Schools - Transfers Allocations Overview of Oversubscribed Schools 2008

 

The following information is included with the outcome letter to tell you in a little more detail about the allocations procedure.  It gives you the cut-off points/distances by which the last child was offered a place at the secondary school according to the school’s admission criteria.  You should read this information carefully, but bear in mind that the allocation process continues as vacancies arise so these details are only accurate as at the time this letter was printed, 3rd March 2008.

 

For these schools, highest priority is given to children with a Statement of Special Educational Needs and Looked After children and they will have been offered above Catchment children. In addition, a small number of children may be admitted on exceptional grounds over and above the normal admissions criteria.

 

It is important to note that offers are made according to how you ranked your preferred schools and whether your child met the criteria for those schools.

 

For Redbridge schools which are their own admitting authorities, details about how places were allocated are available direct from those schools – see the second page of the enclosed letter for those schools.

 

With regard to places allocated at the Redbridge grammar schools, if your child took both the December 2007/January 2008 tests, the test results letter has been posted to you separately, by first class post today.

This data gives you a little more detail about the allocations procedure. It gives you the cut of points/distances by which the last child was offered a place at oversubscribed Community Primary Schools, in accordance with the Authority’s agreed admissions criteria. You should read this information carefully, but please bear in mind that the allocations process continues as vacancies arise, so these details are only accurate at the time the snapshot was taken.

It is important to note that offers are made according to how you ranked your preferred schools and whether your child met the criteria for those schools.

For Redbridge schools which are their own admitting authorities - these are the Catholic primary schools, Jewish schools and Church schools - for details of how places were allocated you should contact the school directly.

You should read this information carefully, but please bear in mind that the allocations process continues as vacancies arise, so these details are only accurate at the time the snapshot was taken.

It is important to note that offers are made according to how you ranked your preferred schools and whether your child met the criteria for those schools.

For the schools listed in the table, highest priority is given to children with a Statement of Special Educational Needs and Looked After children and they will have been offered above Catchment children. In addition, a small number of children may be admitted on exceptional grounds over and above the normal admissions criteria.

For Redbridge schools which are their own ‘Admission Authority’ details about how places were allocated are available direct from those schools.

Note: 'Pupils whose first language is English' includes 'Not known but believed to be English'.

Note: 'Pupils whose first language is not English' includes 'Not known but believed to be other than English'.

Source: DfE: National Curriculum Assessments at Key Stage 2 in England 2011/2012 (Revised)

inv:Dataset.inv:Title: Opportunity Sites
inv:Dataset.inv:Description: The identification of an opportunity site enables the Council (and its partners) to safeguard sites for specific uses, particularly to ensure delivery of the required social and community infrastructure in the area, whilst maximising the development potential of the land. Designation as an opportunity site may present a number of options, including (but not limited to) total redevelopment, partial redevelopment, replacement or refurbishment of the existing buildings, conversion and changes of use. The inclusion of a site does not automatically mean that a planning application will be approved. All proposals will have to comply with a range of other policies found in this Area Action Plan and the rest of the Local Development Framework.

inv:Dataset.inv:Title: Town Centres
inv:Dataset.inv:Description: The Town Centres in Redbridge fall into three categories, Metropolitan, District and Local. Metropolitan Centres, major shopping and commercial centres with a catchment far larger than a single Borough, with good public transport links to a wide variety of destinations. Ilford is the one Metropolitan Centre in Redbridge. District Centres, medium sized shopping and commercial centre providing for more than a local catchment. Some non-retail employment is normally located in these centres. Local Centres, a small number of shops serving local needs.

inv:Dataset.inv:Title: RIPA Applications
inv:Dataset.inv:Description:
The Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act 2000 (RIPA) provides for, and regulates the use of, a range of investigatory powers by a variety of public authorities. The Act deals with a number of areas:

  • updating the law on the interception of communications – to take account of technological change such as the growth of the internet
  • putting other intrusive investigatory techniques on a statutory footing for the first time
  • providing new powers dealing with encryption – to help combat the threat posed by criminal use
  • ensuring that there is independent judicial oversight of the powers in the Act.

Some of the areas are wholly or partially not applicable to the London Borough of Redbridge. However, there are a number of issues arising from the Act that our Authority needs to deal with. Part II of the Act is relevant to the London Borough of Redbridge and includes Directed Surveillance and Covert Human Intelligence Sources.

Redbridge Council uses all powers at its disposal to investigate fraud and criminal matters. The powers under the Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act 2000 (RIPA) have only been used after careful consideration and strictly in accordance with the act. The use of these powers has resulted in a number of successful conclusions to benefit fraud and criminal investigations.

inv:Dataset.inv:Title: Disabled Persons Freedom Pass: Applications
inv:Dataset.inv:Description:
Disabled Persons Freedom Pass

You can apply for the Disabled Persons Freedom Pass if:

  • you are not yet eligible for the Older Persons Freedom Pass and
  • your sole or principal residence is in Redbridge and
  • you have at least one of the seven qualifying disabilities (as per below) such that you:
  1. are blind or partially sighted
  2. are profoundly or severely deaf
  3. are without speech
  4. have a disability or have suffered an injury which has a substantial and long-term adverse effect on your ability to walk
  5. do not have any arms or have long-term loss of the use of both arms
  6. have a learning disability, that is, a state of arrested or incomplete development of mind, which includes significant impairment of intelligence and social functioning
  7. would, if you applied for a driving licence under Part III of the Road Traffic Act 1988, have your application refused pursuant to section 92 of the Act (physical fitness) other than on the grounds of persistent misuse of drugs or alcohol.

inv:Dataset.inv:Title: Housing/Council Tax Benefit Appeals Received
inv:Dataset.inv:Description:
Appeals against a Housing/Council Tax Benefit decision

When you receive a Housing Benefit decision you have one month from the date of the entitlement letter to appeal. An appeal must be in writing and signed. The letter needs to give enough details to identify the decision you appealed against.

We will look at the decision again. If it changed in your favour you will be told of the new decision. If this happens but you are not happy with the new decision you must make a new appeal within one month of the new decision.

If we do not change our decision your appeal will be sent to the Tribunals Service.

inv:Dataset.inv:Title: Business Rate empty property list
inv:Dataset.inv:Description:
A list of empty Business Rate (commercial) properties held in Council Tax records.

The Council’s Payments and Benefits service holds through its Council Tax records information regarding empty properties owned both by individuals and non-individuals.  The Council’s policy in responding to the requests received is to disclose information of empty properties only if they are owned by a company or someone other than an individual in their personal capacity.

The Council’s policy is based on the Information Commissioner’s decision in a case involving the London Borough of Bexley (see Information Tribunal Appeals Numbers: EA/2006/0060 and EA 2006/0066). In this case, Bexley argued that disclosure of a list of empty properties would, amongst other things, lead to an increase in crime and that, as such, disclosure was not in the public interest. In contrast, the Information Commissioner held that it is in the public interest to disclose the lists of empty properties, but for properties owned by private individuals the public interest in protecting those individuals from the risk of crime outweighs the public interest in disclosing this information. However, the Information Commissioner did  not consider the public interest position to be the same for properties owned by companies or commercial entities and held that the identity of empty properties owned by these entities should be disclosed. 

Following the Bexley case, the case of Voyias v ICO & LB Camden (decision 2/9/11) held that the public interest in disclosure of a list of void properties where a non-individual is listed as the owner outweighed the public interest in withholding that information even though Section 31 of the Freedom of Information Act might apply. The case also stated that (for that instance at least) the information contained on Council Tax lists (in so far as those lists relate to properties owned by private individuals) was not caught by the request and did not have to be provided.

In light of the above cases, the Council  is currently refusing to provide lists of addresses of  empty residential properties where the property is owned by individuals. In making such refusals the Council refers to the following exemptions contained within the Act:

Section 31(1)(a) Law Enforcement - where disclosure would prejudice the prevention of crime.

Section 40(2) Personal Data other than that of the requestor – where disclosure would breach the data protection principles contained in the Data Protection Act 1998– in relation to empty properties owned by individuals.

The exemption contained in Section 31 (Law Enforcement), requires the Council to consider the public interest when weighing up disclosure or withholding the requested information. Whilst the Council recognises that there is a public interest in enabling empty properties to be brought back into use, the Council also recognises that there is a public interest in reducing potential criminal activity in empty properties, especially those owned by private individuals. The Council also recognises the potential for empty properties to be subject to squatting and whilst the Council acknowledges that squatting itself is not a criminal activity, the Council considers that squatting often leads to the commission of criminal offences. On this basis it is the Council’s opinion that the public interest favours maintaining the Section 31 exemption and withholding the requested information.

inv:Dataset.inv:Title: Civil Engineering Structures - Heights
inv:Dataset.inv:Description:
There are many roads within the London Borough of Redbridge that are supported and carried by structures owned or maintained by the Borough.

These highways structures are bridges, subways, culverts and retaining walls that vary in age, size and type and material of construction.

The bridges vary from a simple single span bridge to a multi-span bridge going across roads, water courses and railway lines.

The material of construction of these structures consists of masonry, reinforced concrete and steel or a combination of these materials to form composite structures.

Some of these structures beneath or over roads owned or maintained by the Borough are themselves owned by the London Borough of Redbridge (LBR). Other structures within the Borough are owned or maintained by Transport for London (Tfl), Network Rail (NR), London Underground Limited (LUL) and Thames Water (TA).

LBR owned/maintained structures are routinely inspected and maintained.

Buildings deteriorate constantly and improvement and repair work is undertaken frequently but it is not possible to maintain condition data with sufficient frequency to ensure that it always reflects current building condition.)

inv:Dataset.inv:Title: Extra Care Sheltered Housing
inv:Dataset.inv:Description:
Extra care housing enables people to continue to live independently in their own home for as long as possible by providing 24-hour care and support.

It is different because you are living at home with your own front door (not in a home). The aim of extra care housing is to have a ‘home for life’.

Extra care housing can also be called sheltered housing.

inv:Dataset.inv:Title: Average Salary
inv:Dataset.inv:Description:
Average salaries of employees based on employees scale point value as at the report date, taking into account hours worked.

 

This data includes all Council employees. Employees from schools and agency staff are excluded. Casual workers, who work on an ad hoc basis, are excluded from this data.

 

For the figure excluding chief officer and above, employees paid from the payment table ‘JNC – Chief Officers & Chief Exec’ are excluded from all values.

 

Salaries included in this data take into account employees working hours and weeks. The numerator is defined as the total of scale point value for each position. This is taken from all occupied positions as at the reporting date. The denominator is the total FTE (full time equivalent) of employees.

 

Worked Example

 

Total value of scale points * FTE = FTE Salary Value

 

FTE Salary Value / Headcount = Average Salary

inv:Dataset.inv:Title: Life expectancy at birth by ward
inv:Dataset.inv:Description: Life expectancy at birth for an area in each time period is an estimate of the average number of years a new-born baby would survive if he or she experienced the particular area’s age-specific mortality rates for that time period throughout his or her life. The figure reflects mortality among those living in the area in each time period, rather than mortality among those born in each area. It is not therefore the number of years a baby born in the area in each time period could actually expect to live, both because the death rates of the area are likely to change in the future and because many of those born in the area will live elsewhere for at least some part of their lives.

inv:Resource.inv:Title: Life expectancy at birth by ward
inv:Resource.inv:Description: The theoretical time an average person born today would live if he or she had the same rate of death at each age as people who are alive at the moment.

inv:Rendition.inv:Description: The theoretical time an average person born today would live if he or she had the same rate of death at each age as people who are alive at the moment.

inv:Dataset.inv:Title: Standardised Mortality Ratio for all causes, all ages
inv:Dataset.inv:Description:
SMRs should only be compared to the index rate (in this case
England). An SMR higher than 100 indicates a rate that is higher than
England, but the rate cannot be compared to other small areas eg
ward x has a higher rate than ward y.
Trends are presented using the England rates for 2006-2010 as the
index rate.

inv:Resource.inv:Title: Standardised Mortality Ratio for all causes, all ages
inv:Resource.inv:Description: An SMR is defined as the ratio of the observed number of deaths in an area to the number expected if the area had the same age-specific rates as England. For presentational purposes, this ratio is multiplied by 100.

inv:Dataset.inv:Title: National Child Measurement Programme - Reception year
inv:Dataset.inv:Description:
The National Child Measurement Programme (NCMP) is an important element of the Government’s work programme on childhood obesity, and is operated jointly by the Department of Health (DH) and the Department for Education (DfE).

Every year, as part of the NCMP, children in Reception (aged 4-5 years) and Year 6 (aged 10-11 years) have their height and weight measured during the school year to inform local planning and delivery of services for children; and gather population-level surveillance data to allow analysis of trends in growth patterns and obesity.

The NCMP also helps to increase public and professional understanding of weight issues in children and is a useful vehicle for engaging with children and families about healthy lifestyles and weight issues.

The Obesity Learning Centre website hosts a NCMP network area with information on the NCMP, latest news items, and links to resources. There are also discussion boards to post and discuss NCMP work. This network area is closed access; new users will need to register before accessing the resources.

inv:Resource.inv:Title: National Child Measurement Programme - Reception year
inv:Resource.inv:Description: The National Child Measurement Programme annually weighs and measures children in reception year and year six in maintained schools in England. The programme began in 2005 and provides the most robust source of childhood obesity data in England.

inv:Rendition.inv:Description: The National Child Measurement Programme annually weighs and measures children in reception year and year six in maintained schools in England. The programme began in 2005 and provides the most robust source of childhood obesity data in England.

inv:Dataset.inv:Title: Standardised Admission Ratio by cause, age and gender
inv:Dataset.inv:Description:
An Standardised Admission Ratio (SAR) is defined as the ratio of the observed number of admissions in an area to the number expected if the area had the same age specific rates as England.

 

For presentational purposes, this ratio is multiplied by 100.

 

Standardised Admission Ratios should only be compared to the index rate (in this case England). An SAR higher than 100 indicates a rate that is higher than England, but the rate cannot be compared to other small areas eg: ward x has a higher rate than ward y.

inv:Dataset.inv:Title: Standardised Mortality Ratio in under 75 years by cause and gender
inv:Dataset.inv:Description:
An Standardised Mortality Ratio (SMR) is defined as the ratio of the observed number of deaths in an area to the number expected if the area had the same age-specific rates as England. For presentational purposes, this ratio is multiplied by 100.

 

SMRs should only be compared to the index rate (in this case England). An SMR higher than 100 indicates a rate that is higher than England, but the rate cannot be compared to other small areas eg: ward x has a higher rate than ward y.

inv:Dataset.inv:Title: Automatic Traffic Counter (Portable) Statistics
inv:Dataset.inv:Description:
These portable Automatic Traffic Counters are laid across the roads by the Council in various locations throughout the Borough to record both volumes of traffic and speed.

The data collected is over a seven day, 24 hour period and is used to assist decision making in respect of traffic calming measures, reports and indicators for projections to support future Borough work schemes on the roads, funding permitting.

inv:Dataset.inv:Title: Automatic Traffic Counter (Permanent) Statistics
inv:Dataset.inv:Description:
These sites are laid to monitor traffic speeds and flows at all major entries and exits both to and from the Borough.

As well as these there are additional sites laid across the Borough to monitor the "through traffic" position.

This data is collected over a 7 day, 24 hour period and used to assist decision making in respect of reports and indicatorsfor projections to supply future Borough schemes (for the monitored reduction of trafficvolumes and associated pollution).

Please note the figures given are the average daily count; any fractional part of the average is not displayed.
